english:
  title: Reflections
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Long have I wandered as a guest, still wrapped in summer's cloth,
    while northern winds blow cold and piercing.
    Droplet by droplet, the chill descends—
    orchids wither, their fragrant grace fades away.

    The passes and mountains stretch distant and dim,
    step after step, the road extends endlessly.
    How shall I endure until the year's end?
    When winter comes, the frost falls thick.

    Oh, the spring in the mountain's heart,
    once crystalline and still in that high place—
    but one dawn the embankment breaks,
    and down it pours in torrents.

    With each passing day, the mountains recede,
    many waters converge and flow as one.
    Never again shall it hold that former clarity—
    what has departed, how can it return?

    I have come to stand upon the water's edge,
    yet I cannot bear to hear its voice.

    Where is the phoenix, so free and soaring,
    rising high beyond all mortal sight?
    When hungry, it feeds on green jade bamboo,
    when thirsty, it drinks from Heaven's pool.
    Looking down, the dusty world seems small,
    just the clamor of chickens in a yard.

    This is why it does not descend—
    it spirals endlessly on thousand-fathom peaks.
  footnotes:
    - The phoenix in classical Chinese poetry symbolizes the noble spirit that refuses to compromise with a corrupt world.
    - The broken embankment serves as a metaphor for loss and the inability to restore what has been ruined—possibly reflecting on political or personal upheaval during the author's lifetime.
    - Jeong Do-jeon (1342-1398) was a scholar-official of the Goryeo-Joseon transition period, and this poem likely reflects his observations on change, displacement, and the tension between engagement with the world and withdrawal from it.
